{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XxWrGEUiBW3UYLAkSnWd7u","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/**\n     2→ * Devnet E2E: Verify deep-link URL updates when creating/joining matches.\n     3→ */\n     4→import { test, expect } from \"./fixtures\";\n     5→import * as po from \"../local/helpers/page-objects\";\n     6→import { PLAYER_A } from \"./helpers/wallets\";\n     7→import { validateDevnetEnv, verifyFairnessBackend } from \"./helpers/env\";\n     8→import { Connection, LAMPORTS_PER_SOL } from \"@solana/web3.js\";\n     9→\n    10→test.beforeAll(async () => {\n    11→  const config = validateDevnetEnv();\n    12→  await verifyFairnessBackend(config);\n    13→  const connection = new Connection(config.rpcUrl, \"confirmed\");\n    14→  const balance = await connection.getBalance(PLAYER_A.publicKey);\n    15→  if (balance < 0.05 * LAMPORTS_PER_SOL) {\n    16→    throw new Error(`Player A needs at least 0.05 SOL, has ${balance / LAMPORTS_PER_SOL}`);\n    17→  }\n    18→});\n    19→\n    20→test(\"coinflip: URL updates to /coinflip/:matchId after creating a match\", async ({\n    21→  playerAPage,\n    22→}) => {\n    23→  test.setTimeout(120_000);\n    24→\n    25→  // Capture browser console for debugging\n    26→  playerAPage.on(\"console\", (msg) => {\n    27→    const text = msg.text();\n    28→    if (text.includes(\"[coinflip]\") || text.includes(\"matchId\") || text.includes(\"replaceState\")) {\n    29→      console.log(`[browser] ${text}`);\n    30→    }\n    31→  });\n    32→\n    33→  // Navigate to coinflip\n    34→  await po.navigateToCoinflip(playerAPage);\n    35→  console.log(\"[deeplink] URL before create:\", playerAPage.url());\n    36→\n    37→  // Create a match\n    38→  await po.createMatch(playerAPage, 0.005, \"heads\", { timeout: 60_000 });\n    39→  console.log(\"[deeplink] URL immediately after create:\", playerAPage.url());\n    40→\n    41→  // Give React a moment to process the state update + effect\n    42→  await playerAPage.waitForTimeout(3_000);\n    43→  console.log(\"[deeplink] URL after 3s:\", playerAPage.url());\n    44→\n    45→  // Check if activeMatch exists in the page by evaluating\n    46→  const debugInfo = await playerAPage.evaluate(() => {\n    47→    return {\n    48→      pathname: window.location.pathname,\n    49→      href: window.location.href,\n    50→    };\n    51→  });\n    52→  console.log(\"[deeplink] window.location:\", JSON.stringify(debugInfo));\n    53→\n    54→  // Poll for URL change\n    55→  await expect(async () => {\n    56→    const url = playerAPage.url();\n    57→    expect(url).toMatch(/\\/coinflip\\/[0-9a-f]{16}/i);\n    58→  }).toPass({ timeout: 15_000, intervals: [1_000] });\n    59→\n    60→  console.log(\"[deeplink] Final URL:\", playerAPage.url());\n    61→});\n    62→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1de1cbce-bcf6-4659-9a0e-c65f55d25303","uuid":"92dda184-e68c-4419-85f1-b6368a42bdd2","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/sources/rng-utopia/apps/platform/e2e/devnet/deeplink.spec.ts","content":"/**\n * Devnet E2E: Verify deep-link URL updates when creating/joining matches.\n */\nimport { test, expect } from \"./fixtures\";\nimport * as po from \"../local/helpers/page-objects\";\nimport { PLAYER_A } from \"./helpers/wallets\";\nimport { validateDevnetEnv, verifyFairnessBackend } from \"./helpers/env\";\nimport { Connection, LAMPORTS_PER_SOL } from \"@solana/web3.js\";\n\ntest.beforeAll(async () => {\n  const config = validateDevnetEnv();\n  await verifyFairnessBackend(config);\n  const connection = new Connection(config.rpcUrl, \"confirmed\");\n  const balance = await connection.getBalance(PLAYER_A.publicKey);\n  if (balance < 0.05 * LAMPORTS_PER_SOL) {\n    throw new Error(`Player A needs at least 0.05 SOL, has ${balance / LAMPORTS_PER_SOL}`);\n  }\n});\n\ntest(\"coinflip: URL updates to /coinflip/:matchId after creating a match\", async ({\n  playerAPage,\n}) => {\n  test.setTimeout(120_000);\n\n  // Capture browser console for debugging\n  playerAPage.on(\"console\", (msg) => {\n    const text = msg.text();\n    if (text.includes(\"[coinflip]\") || text.includes(\"matchId\") || text.includes(\"replaceState\")) {\n      console.log(`[browser] ${text}`);\n    }\n  });\n\n  // Navigate to coinflip\n  await po.navigateToCoinflip(playerAPage);\n  console.log(\"[deeplink] URL before create:\", playerAPage.url());\n\n  // Create a match\n  await po.createMatch(playerAPage, 0.005, \"heads\", { timeout: 60_000 });\n  console.log(\"[deeplink] URL immediately after create:\", playerAPage.url());\n\n  // Give React a moment to process the state update + effect\n  await playerAPage.waitForTimeout(3_000);\n  console.log(\"[deeplink] URL after 3s:\", playerAPage.url());\n\n  // Check if activeMatch exists in the page by evaluating\n  const debugInfo = await playerAPage.evaluate(() => {\n    return {\n      pathname: window.location.pathname,\n      href: window.location.href,\n    };\n  });\n  console.log(\"[deeplink] window.location:\", JSON.stringify(debugInfo));\n\n  // Poll for URL change\n  await expect(async () => {\n    const url = playerAPage.url();\n    expect(url).toMatch(/\\/coinflip\\/[0-9a-f]{16}/i);\n  }).toPass({ timeout: 15_000, intervals: [1_000] });\n\n  console.log(\"[deeplink] Final URL:\", playerAPage.url());\n});\n","numLines":62,"startLine":1,"totalLines":62}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UJFdj1gSzN2DnaiGa6FQys","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. **Update `helpers/env.ts`**: Add `closecallProgramId` (optional, like lordofrngs) + verify deployment\n2. **Create `closecall-lifecycle.spec.ts`**: The devnet E2E test\n\nFor the test, the approach:\n- **Smoke tier**: Always runs\n  - Closecall program deployed + executable\n  - Pyth BTC/USD price account exists and readable on devnet\n  - Backend closecall API responds: `GET /closecall/current-round`, `GET /closecall/history`\n\n\n- **Lifecycle tier**: Conditional — only if a round is available\n  - Poll for an open round with betting window still open\n  - Player A and B place bets (GREEN and RED) via on-chain transactions\n  - Wait for settlement and verify outcome, payouts, and round details\n\nActually, I'm realizing the existing tests interact through the UI rather than direct on-chain calls. The coinflip and lord tests use UI interactions like clicking buttons and waiting for selectors, so I should probably follow that same pattern for Close Call instead of bypassing the UI.\n\nFor the UI flow, I'd navigate to the Close Call page, wait for the chart and round to load, enter a bet amount, click the color button, and wait for settlement. The challenge is that this depends on the clock worker having created a round, which requires fresh Pyth prices.\n\nGiven the Pyth staleness issue, I'm thinking a two-tier approach makes sense: a smoke test to validate the infrastructure (program deployed, Pyth account readable, backend responding), then a conditional lifecycle test that runs the full UI flow only if a round is actually available. Let me start designing this, beginning with what I need to know about the on-chain program itself.\n\nI'll need to add the Close Call program ID and Pyth price account as environment variables for validation, then structure the test file with a beforeAll hook to validate the environment and check wallet funding, followed by the infrastructure test that verifies the program is deployed and the Pyth account is readable.\n\nWriting the test file structure... I'm realizing this approach is too brittle—the lifecycle test would be flaky with Pyth staleness issues. Instead, I should focus on what the spec actually requires: real-provider E2E coverage that validates the Pyth oracle integration on devnet. The practical minimum is checking that the closecall program deploys, the Pyth price account is readable, the backend API responds, and if a round exists, its data is structurally sound with real prices. I'll start by updating the environment config to include the closecall program ID.\n\nNow I need to update the deployment verification function to check the closecall program, then write a focused test file that validates the oracle infrastructure in one test and conditionally runs a lifecycle test only if betting conditions align—using the UI approach for consistency with existing tests, though I'm second-guessing whether direct on-chain transactions would be more reliable.\n\nSince the Close Call frontend doesn't have page objects yet, I'll work with the CSS class selectors directly and build a straightforward test flow: navigate to the route, wait for round data, skip if nothing appears, then place bets for both players and verify settlement through on-chain reads.\n\nFor the test strategy, I'll keep it consistent with the existing lifecycle tests—UI for player actions, backend API for polling round availability and settlement, and on-chain reads to verify the Pyth integration and program state. If the clock worker isn't creating rounds due to stale Pyth prices, the infrastructure test still passes (proving the components work) while the lifecycle test gracefully skips with a clear reason.\n\nWriting the test file now...\n\nDefining the test structure... Setting up test constants and configuration... Defining the backend round interface... Writing async polling functions... Writing utility functions... Writing test setup... Writing test assertions... Writing test setup... Writing test navigation and bet placement... Writing test assertions... Verifying that Player B's red bet appears in the backend round data, then waiting for the round to settle and checking the final outcome and closing price... Still writing test assertions...\n\nFor refund rounds, I'm verifying no fee was collected, then confirming both players see the settlement reflected in the UI. Now I'm navigating to the round details page to validate that the settlement information displays correctly.\n\nAfter that, I'm filtering out noise from the console logs for both players and asserting that there are no unexpected errors from either side.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether this lifecycle test is actually feasible given the constraints. The betting window is only 30 seconds, and both players need to place bets within that timeframe while the clock worker creates rounds at minute boundaries with a 2-second offset. There's also the risk that Pyth devnet prices could be stale, blocking round creation entirely. The test would need to handle navigation, input, clicking, and waiting for transaction confirmation all within that 30-second window.\n\nI could make this work by detecting when the betting window opens, skipping the test if there's less than 15 seconds remaining, and using direct URL navigation instead of clicking through the UI. But I'm also wondering if it makes more sense to validate the oracle integration at the API or on-chain level instead of trying to orchestrate all this through the UI.\n\nLooking at what the checklist actually asks for—end-to-end coverage of the devnet real-provider with environment validation and retry logic—I realize the core requirement is proving that the oracle integration pipeline works: the program reads Pyth prices correctly, the backend creates and settles rounds with real prices, and the API serves the correct data. Unlike the coinflip or lord tests where player actions drive the UI, Close Call's oracle integration is entirely backend and on-chain. So I should create a test that validates this pipeline without requiring UI bet placement, which is the timing-sensitive part. The test can verify the infrastructure, wait for a round to be created and settled, and confirm the oracle pipeline works end-to-end. Verify the settled round has consistent Pyth price data, and optionally place a bet if timing allows. This is more realistic and less flaky. The lifecycle test with UI bet placement could be a separate, more advanced test that can be skipped.\n\nLooking at existing coverage, the bankrun tests already handle all 6 instructions with mock Pyth data, visual tests cover UI rendering, and local E2E isn't applicable since Pyth isn't on localnet. What the devnet test uniquely provides is real Pyth oracle integration, the clock worker lifecycle creating and settling rounds with actual prices, and backend API responses with real oracle data.\n\nSo the minimum viable test validates that the program is deployed and executable, the Pyth account is readable, the backend API is responding, and there's evidence of successful oracle-resolved rounds in the history. The lifecycle portion—placing bets and verifying settlement—can be optional and more resilient: wait for a round but skip if none appears within the timeout, check that the betting window has enough time remaining, and only place bets if conditions are favorable. This way the infrastructure tier always passes while the lifecycle tier gracefully degrades if timing doesn't work out. for settlement → verify\n\nLet me also handle the case where the betting window closes between Player A and Player B betting. In that case, Player B's bet would fail, and we should handle that gracefully.\n\nActually, let me simplify even further. The lifecycle test can try to place bets but gracefully handle all failure modes:\n- No round → skip\n- Betting window too short → skip  \n- Bet tx fails → log and continue (verify what we can)\n- Settlement timeout → log and fail\n\nOK, let me just write the final version now. I'm going to keep it practical.\n\nActually, I just realized something important. Looking at the Pyth staleness issue from iteration 8: devnet Pyth updates every ~5 minutes instead of every second like mainnet, and with MAX_OPEN_PRICE_AGE_SECS=60, the clock worker will frequently fail to create rounds. So the lifecycle test will be flaky. The honest approach is to make the infra test robust, keep the lifecycle test conditional with clear documentation about why it might skip, and still run it when conditions allow.\n\nNow I need to calculate the remaining betting time by taking the round's createdAt timestamp, adding 30 seconds for the betting window, and comparing against the current time. If less than 15 seconds remain, I should wait for the next round instead.\n\nWriting the final code...\n\nI also need to make closecallProgramId optional in the env configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2685,"cache_read_input_tokens":71454,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2685},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1de1cbce-bcf6-4659-9a0e-c65f55d25303","uuid":"b182b699-7404-47b8-bb63-cf59a794bbeb"}
